#Text=collapse breccia :  A mass of rock composed of angular to rounded fragments of limestone or dolomite that has formed as the result of the collapse of the roof of a cave, of an underlying cave, or of an overhanging ledge. See also solution breccia.
#Text=collapse sink :  A closed depression formed by the collapse of tie roof of a cave. See also doline.
#Text=column :  A flowstone formation, generally cylindrical, formed by the union of a stalactite and stalagmite. See also pillar.
#Text=conduit :  A subterranean stream course filled completely with water and always under hydrostatic pressure. See also siphon.

#Text=cone karst :  A type of karst topography, common in the tropicr. characterized by star-shaped depressions at the feet of many steep-sided core-shaped hills. A variety of Kegelkarst. See also cockpit karst.
#Text=constructive waterfall :  A large rimstone dam on a surface stream.

#Text=conulite :  A hollow, cone-shaped speleothem formed when a conical depression is drilled in cave mud by falling water. Subsequent erosion may remove the mud, isolating the calcite lining of the depression.
#Text=corridor :  A fairly level and straight passage that links two or more rooms or chambers in a cave.
#Text=corridor :  Intersecting linear depressions on the surface of the land, related to joints or dikes. See also bogaz; struga; zanjon.
#Text=corrosion : Erosion by solution or chemical action. See also corrasion.
#Text=cove :   Narrow steep-sided karst valley flanking limestone plateaus.

#Text=covered karst : A terrain of karst features, usually subdued, resulting from the development of solution features in limestone covered by soil; contrasted with naked karst, which is soil free. See also buried karst.
#Text=crawl, crawlway :  A cave passage that must be negotiated on hands and knees, crescentic wall niche. See meander niche.

#Text=crevice karst : An intricate irregular crevice system that has formed by solution widening of closely spaced joints. Crevices may be as much as 6 meters across and 20 meters deep. Especially well developed near rivers in lowland New Guinea.
#Text=crust stone :  A fragile layer of flowstone covering portions of walls of caves; looks like a flaky crust. Found in some Kentucky caves.
#Text=crystal cave :  A cave in which much of the surface of the roof, walls, and floor is covered with well-formed mineral crystals.
#Text=crystal pool :  In caves a pool, generally having little or no overflow, containing crystals.
#Text=cul-de-sac, dead end :  A subterranean passage having only one entry.
